1
00:00:19,438 --> 00:00:23,942
We've become bored with watching
actors give us phony emotions.

2
00:00:24,693 --> 00:00:28,405
We're tired of pyrotechnics
and special effects.

3
00:00:28,947 --> 00:00:33,785
While the world he inhabits is,
in some respects, counterfeit,

4
00:00:34,745 --> 00:00:37,664
there's nothing fake about
Truman himself.

5
00:00:38,373 --> 00:00:40,959
No scripts, no cue cards.

6
00:00:41,752 --> 00:00:44,796
It isn't always Shakespeare,
but it's genuine.

7
00:00:45,547 --> 00:00:46,965
It's a life.

8
00:00:50,844 --> 00:00:52,763
<i>I'm not going to make it.</i>

9
00:00:54,264 --> 00:00:55,974
<i>You're going to have to go on
without me.</i>

10
00:01:01,313 --> 00:01:02,814
<i>No way, mister.</i>

11
00:01:03,649 --> 00:01:07,486
<i>You're going to the top of this mountain,
broken legs and all.</i>

12
00:01:11,990 --> 00:01:15,160
We find many viewers leave him on
all night for comfort.

13
00:01:16,995 --> 00:01:19,164
<i>You're crazy, you know that?</i>

14
00:01:22,417 --> 00:01:26,588
For me, there is no difference
between a private life and a public life.

15
00:01:26,672 --> 00:01:30,008
My life, is my life, is <i>The Truman Show.</i>

16
00:01:30,092 --> 00:01:32,427
<i>The Truman Show</i> is a lifestyle.

17
00:01:32,511 --> 00:01:34,846
It's a noble life. It is

18
00:01:37,724 --> 00:01:39,309
a truly blessed life.

19
00:01:39,393 --> 00:01:42,020
<i>Yeah, tell me something I don't know.</i>

20
00:01:43,397 --> 00:01:46,149
<i>All right. Promise me one thing, though.</i>

21
00:01:46,858 --> 00:01:49,444
<i>If I die before I reach the summit,</i>

22
00:01:50,404 --> 00:01:53,490
<i>you'll use me
as an alternative source of food.</i>

23
00:01:54,574 --> 00:01:55,659
<i>Gross.</i>

24
00:01:59,162 --> 00:02:01,373
It's all true. It's all real.

25
00:02:01,581 --> 00:02:05,294
Nothing here is fake.
Nothing you see on this show is fake.

26
00:02:05,669 --> 00:02:07,045
It's merely controlled.

27
00:02:15,304 --> 00:02:18,265
Eat me, damn it. That's an order.

28
00:02:21,226 --> 00:02:23,395
Maybe just your love handles.

29
00:02:24,313 --> 00:02:27,941
I have love handles? Yeah. Little ones.

30
00:02:28,233 --> 00:02:30,694
Truman. You're going to be late.

31
00:02:31,278 --> 00:02:32,946
Okay!

32
00:02:47,169 --> 00:02:48,962
- Good morning.
- Morning.

33
00:02:49,046 --> 00:02:50,213
Good morning.

34
00:02:50,297 --> 00:02:54,593
In case I don't see you, good afternoon,
good evening, and good night.

35
00:02:55,552 --> 00:02:56,845
Yeah.

36
00:02:56,928 --> 00:02:58,847
- Morning, Truman.
- Morning, Spencer.

37
00:02:58,930 --> 00:03:00,724
Hey, Pluto. No, get down.

38
00:03:00,807 --> 00:03:02,559
- He won't hurt you.
- Get down.

39
00:03:02,642 --> 00:03:04,186
I know.

40
00:03:04,311 --> 00:03:06,563
- It's just me.
- Come on, Pluto.

41
00:03:28,752 --> 00:03:30,128
What is it?

42
00:03:51,274 --> 00:03:55,529
<i>Here's a news flash just in. An aircraft
in trouble began shedding parts</i>

43
00:03:55,612 --> 00:03:58,698
<i>as it flew over Seahaven
just a few moments ago.</i>

44
00:03:58,782 --> 00:04:00,492
<i>Luckily, no one was hurt.</i>

45
00:04:00,575 --> 00:04:02,661
<i>But, hey, how do you feel today?</i>

46
00:04:02,994 --> 00:04:05,080
<i>That's good.
You thinking of flying somewhere?</i>

47
00:04:05,163 --> 00:04:06,706
- Nope.
<i>- No? Good.</i>

48
00:04:06,790 --> 00:04:08,875
<i>This is Classical Clive
with Classical Drive</i>

49
00:04:08,959 --> 00:04:11,294
<i>so why don't you forget
about the perils of flying,</i>

50
00:04:11,378 --> 00:04:14,381
<i>settle back,
and let this music calm you down?</i>

51
00:04:18,760 --> 00:04:21,179
<i>- Dog Fancy,</i> please.
<i>- Dog Fancy.</i>

52
00:04:21,263 --> 00:04:24,099
- Thank you very much.
- Thank you very much.

53
00:04:24,850 --> 00:04:27,018
Give me a paper there, will you, Earl?

54
00:04:27,102 --> 00:04:30,063
And one of these for the wife.

55
00:04:30,147 --> 00:04:31,940
Loves her fashion mags.

56
00:04:32,023 --> 00:04:33,567
Will that be all for you, Truman?

57
00:04:33,650 --> 00:04:36,027
- That's the whole kit and caboodle.
- Catch you later.

58
00:04:36,111 --> 00:04:38,155
Okay. Yeah.

59
00:04:45,203 --> 00:04:46,663
Good morning.

60
00:04:47,873 --> 00:04:49,833
- Hank.
- Morning, Truman.

61
00:04:50,500 --> 00:04:53,378
- Good morning, Truman.
- How are you guys?

62
00:04:53,462 --> 00:04:55,714
- Beautiful day, isn't it?
- Always.

63
00:04:55,797 --> 00:04:57,424
And how's your lovely wife?

64
00:04:58,633 --> 00:05:00,427
Good. How about yours?

65
00:05:00,510 --> 00:05:03,013
- Couldn't be better.
- Fine.

66
00:05:03,096 --> 00:05:04,931
- Nice talking to you, Truman.
- You, too.

67
00:05:05,015 --> 00:05:06,141
We must go now.

68
00:05:06,224 --> 00:05:09,853
Think about that policy. Okay,
that's two for one. That's a good deal.

69
00:05:09,936 --> 00:05:12,147
- Doppelgänger special.
- Right.

70
00:05:12,230 --> 00:05:13,398
Hi.

71
00:05:16,026 --> 00:05:18,612
Hey, fellows. You going in? Go ahead.

72
00:05:19,571 --> 00:05:21,990
- Go ahead.
- No, you first, please.

73
00:05:22,115 --> 00:05:24,242
I'm not that anxious to get there.

74
00:05:39,216 --> 00:05:40,383
Yes, hello.

75
00:05:40,467 --> 00:05:44,012
Could I have directory assistance
for Fiji, please? Fiji islands.

76
00:05:44,095 --> 00:05:45,514
Truman, did you see this?

77
00:05:48,183 --> 00:05:49,476
I'm sorry, ma'am.

78
00:05:49,559 --> 00:05:52,562
If he's in a coma,
he's probably uninsurable.

79
00:05:54,105 --> 00:05:56,691
Hello? Yes. Fiji, please.

80
00:05:57,067 --> 00:05:59,861
Do you have a listing for
Lauren Garland?

81
00:06:01,071 --> 00:06:02,614
Nothing listed?

82
00:06:03,698 --> 00:06:06,785
Okay. Do you have a Sylvia Garland?

83
00:06:06,952 --> 00:06:08,453
"S" for Sylvia.

84
00:06:09,955 --> 00:06:11,164
Nothing?

85
00:06:13,124 --> 00:06:14,751
Okay. Thank you.

86
00:06:50,620 --> 00:06:52,539
- Lawrence.
- Hey, Burbank.

87
00:06:52,622 --> 00:06:56,042
Got a prospect in Wells Park
I need you to close.

88
00:06:58,461 --> 00:06:59,838
Wells Park?

89
00:07:02,841 --> 00:07:05,969
- On Harbor Island?
- You know another one?

90
00:07:06,052 --> 00:07:09,889
I can't do it.
I have an appointment. Dentist.

91
00:07:12,267 --> 00:07:16,062
You're going to lose a lot more than
your teeth if you don't meet your quota.

92
00:07:16,146 --> 00:07:17,731
Look, Truman,

93
00:07:17,939 --> 00:07:20,442
they're making cutbacks
at the end of this month.

94
00:07:20,525 --> 00:07:23,028
- Cutbacks?
- Yeah. Now, you need this.

95
00:07:23,737 --> 00:07:28,158
Besides, a half-hour across the bay,
a little sea air would do you good.

96
00:07:29,534 --> 00:07:30,744
Thanks.

97
00:07:40,253 --> 00:07:41,421
Hello.

98
00:07:41,504 --> 00:07:44,674
Ferry's still here.
Thought I might have missed it.

99
00:07:45,008 --> 00:07:46,676
One-way or return?

100
00:07:47,761 --> 00:07:48,970
Return.

101
00:07:51,473 --> 00:07:53,141
There you go, sir.

102
00:08:50,907 --> 00:08:54,452
- Do you need any help, sir?
- You go ahead. I'll be fine.

103
00:08:56,079 --> 00:08:57,288
Yeah.

104
00:09:10,802 --> 00:09:12,137
Hi, honey.

105
00:09:13,805 --> 00:09:16,307
Look what I got free at the checkout.

106
00:09:17,475 --> 00:09:21,062
It's a Chef's Pal.
It's a dicer, grater, peeler, all in one.

107
00:09:21,146 --> 00:09:23,898
Never needs sharpening,
dishwasher-safe.

108
00:09:23,982 --> 00:09:24,983
Wow!

109
00:09:26,109 --> 00:09:27,652
That's amazing.

110
00:09:28,820 --> 00:09:30,071
Truman,

111
00:09:31,614 --> 00:09:33,283
you missed a spot.

112
00:09:47,505 --> 00:09:49,048
That is a beer.

113
00:09:51,176 --> 00:09:53,720
You know, I'm thinking
about getting out, Marlon.

114
00:09:53,803 --> 00:09:55,722
Yeah? Out of what?

115
00:09:56,014 --> 00:09:58,349
Out of my job, out of Seahaven.

116
00:09:58,933 --> 00:10:01,269
- Off this island. Out.
- Out of your job?

117
00:10:01,352 --> 00:10:04,439
What the hell's wrong with your job?
You have a great job, Truman.

118
00:10:04,522 --> 00:10:07,942
You have a desk job.
I'd kill for a desk job.

119
00:10:10,862 --> 00:10:11,988
Here you go.

120
00:10:12,071 --> 00:10:14,491
You should try stocking
vending machines for a living.

121
00:10:14,574 --> 00:10:17,202
- No, thanks.
- Now there's excitement.

122
00:10:17,869 --> 00:10:20,497
Don't you ever get antsy? Itchy feet?

123
00:10:22,040 --> 00:10:23,833
Where's there to go?

124
00:10:25,710 --> 00:10:26,795
Fiji.

125
00:10:28,296 --> 00:10:30,840
Where the hell's Fiji? Near Florida?

126
00:10:36,429 --> 00:10:37,806
- See here?
- Yeah.

127
00:10:37,889 --> 00:10:39,349
This is us,

128
00:10:41,351 --> 00:10:43,561
and all the way around here,

129
00:10:44,145 --> 00:10:45,230
Fiji.

130
00:10:46,147 --> 00:10:49,901
You can't get any further away
before you start coming back.

131
00:10:50,109 --> 00:10:52,862
You know, there are still islands in Fiji

132
00:10:52,946 --> 00:10:54,989
where no human being
has ever set foot.

133
00:10:58,159 --> 00:11:00,370
So when are you going to go?

134
00:11:02,956 --> 00:11:04,749
It's not that simple.

135
00:11:05,792 --> 00:11:07,919
It takes money,

136
00:11:08,920 --> 00:11:10,213
planning.

137
00:11:10,713 --> 00:11:12,590
I can't just up and go.

138
00:11:13,424 --> 00:11:14,592
Right.

139
00:11:15,301 --> 00:11:18,221
I'm going to do it.
Don't worry about that.

140
00:11:18,930 --> 00:11:21,516
Bonus time is just around the corner.

141
00:11:26,229 --> 00:11:29,524
- You coming for a drink?
- No, I can't tonight.

142
00:11:48,960 --> 00:11:52,422
I don't like the look of that weather, son.
I think we should head back.

143
00:11:52,505 --> 00:11:55,049
- No, Dad. Not yet.
- No, come on. We should go back.

144
00:11:55,133 --> 00:11:57,677
- A bit farther, please?
- Son, listen.

145
00:11:58,136 --> 00:11:59,971
- Okay.
- Yes.

146
00:12:02,056 --> 00:12:03,808
Daddy!

147
00:13:18,800 --> 00:13:21,386
You're soaked. Where have you been?

148
00:13:21,469 --> 00:13:23,680
I figure we can
scrape together $8,000...

149
00:13:23,763 --> 00:13:25,139
Every time you and Marlon
get together...

150
00:13:25,223 --> 00:13:27,308
We can bum around the world
for a year on that.

151
00:13:27,392 --> 00:13:31,145
And then what, Truman?
We'd be where we were five years ago.

152
00:13:31,562 --> 00:13:35,692
- You're talking like a teenager.
- Maybe I feel like a teenager.

153
00:13:36,275 --> 00:13:38,736
We have mortgage payments, Truman.

154
00:13:39,028 --> 00:13:40,405
We have car payments.

155
00:13:40,488 --> 00:13:43,616
What, we're just going to walk away
from our financial obligations?

156
00:13:43,700 --> 00:13:45,702
It would be an adventure.

157
00:13:46,160 --> 00:13:50,832
I thought we were going to try for a
baby. Isn't that enough of an adventure?

158
00:13:51,749 --> 00:13:54,252
That can wait. I want to get away.

159
00:13:54,335 --> 00:13:57,088
See some of the world, explore.

160
00:13:57,171 --> 00:14:00,091
Honey, you want to be an explorer?

161
00:14:01,467 --> 00:14:02,927
This'll pass.

162
00:14:04,012 --> 00:14:06,556
We all think like this now and then.

163
00:14:08,975 --> 00:14:11,769
Let's get you out of these wet clothes,

164
00:14:12,270 --> 00:14:13,688
come to bed.

165
00:14:15,023 --> 00:14:17,984
You never see anything anyway.
They always

166
00:14:18,067 --> 00:14:20,987
turn the camera and play music and,

167
00:14:21,446 --> 00:14:24,198
you know, the wind blows in,
and the curtains move

168
00:14:24,282 --> 00:14:25,700
and you don't see anything.

169
00:14:30,705 --> 00:14:32,957
<i>- Dog Fancy,</i> please.
<i>- Dog Fancy.</i>

170
00:14:34,208 --> 00:14:35,543
Thank you.

171
00:14:37,462 --> 00:14:39,589
- Paper, Earl, please.
- Paper.

172
00:14:41,174 --> 00:14:44,552
I might as well pick one of these up
while I'm at it.

173
00:14:44,677 --> 00:14:47,305
- For the wife?
- She's got to have them.

174
00:14:47,930 --> 00:14:50,975
- Anything else, Truman?
- That's the whole ball of wax.

175
00:14:51,476 --> 00:14:53,394
- Catch you later.
- Okay.

176
00:15:14,248 --> 00:15:15,333
Dad?

177
00:15:18,669 --> 00:15:20,379
What are you doing?

178
00:15:20,671 --> 00:15:23,716
What the... Get out of the way!

179
00:15:24,008 --> 00:15:25,343
Stop them!

180
00:15:27,845 --> 00:15:29,514
Stop those people!

181
00:15:32,642 --> 00:15:35,978
Open the doors!
Somebody, stop the bus!

182
00:15:36,395 --> 00:15:39,190
Stop the bus! Somebody, stop it!

183
00:15:40,108 --> 00:15:42,276
Somebody, stop the bus!

184
00:15:55,748 --> 00:15:58,668
And wasn't it funny...

185
00:16:04,632 --> 00:16:07,343
It doesn't sound insane at all, Truman.

186
00:16:07,552 --> 00:16:11,305
I see him 10 times a week
in 100 different faces.

187
00:16:11,472 --> 00:16:15,309
I almost hugged a perfect stranger
in the salon last Thursday.

188
00:16:15,393 --> 00:16:18,980
It was Dad. I swear.
Dressed like a homeless man.

189
00:16:19,480 --> 00:16:20,982
And you know what else was strange?

190
00:16:21,065 --> 00:16:23,067
A businessman and a woman
with a little dog

191
00:16:23,151 --> 00:16:25,778
came out of nowhere
and forced him onto a bus.

192
00:16:25,862 --> 00:16:28,656
It's about time they cleaned up
the trash downtown

193
00:16:28,739 --> 00:16:31,450
before we become
just like the rest of the country.

194
00:16:31,534 --> 00:16:34,078
They never found Dad's body.
Maybe somehow...

195
00:16:34,162 --> 00:16:35,163
God!

196
00:16:35,246 --> 00:16:38,541
I'm telling you, if it wasn't him,
it was his twin.

197
00:16:40,001 --> 00:16:44,046
- Did Dad have a brother?
- Truman, you know perfectly well

198
00:16:44,422 --> 00:16:48,801
that your father was an only child,
just like you.

199
00:16:51,512 --> 00:16:53,055
Now, sweetie,

200
00:16:53,723 --> 00:16:56,893
you're just feeling bad
because of what happened.

201
00:16:58,144 --> 00:17:01,105
You, sailing off into that storm.

202
00:17:04,275 --> 00:17:06,777
But I've never blamed you, Truman,

203
00:17:07,904 --> 00:17:09,947
and I don't blame you now.

204
00:17:56,202 --> 00:17:57,411
Truman?

205
00:18:01,457 --> 00:18:03,668
What are you doing down here?

206
00:18:05,169 --> 00:18:06,796
Fixing the mower.

207
00:18:10,466 --> 00:18:12,677
- Saw my father today.
- I know.

208
00:18:16,013 --> 00:18:17,765
Your mother called.

209
00:18:19,600 --> 00:18:22,395
You really shouldn't upset her like that.

210
00:18:22,561 --> 00:18:25,064
Did you want... What did you want?

211
00:18:25,439 --> 00:18:27,024
I made macaroni.

212
00:18:27,692 --> 00:18:29,193
I'm not hungry.

213
00:18:30,027 --> 00:18:33,656
You know, you really ought to throw out
that mower.

214
00:18:34,824 --> 00:18:37,243
Get one of those new Elk Rotaries.

215
00:19:13,821 --> 00:19:15,406
What's he doing?

216
00:19:15,531 --> 00:19:18,492
See, they got rid of her,
but they couldn't erase the memory.

217
00:19:18,576 --> 00:19:20,244
The memory of who?

218
00:20:12,963 --> 00:20:15,299
- You okay? You all right?
- Excuse me. Hi.

219
00:20:15,383 --> 00:20:17,635
- Hi.
- I'm so sorry I fell on you like that.

220
00:20:17,718 --> 00:20:20,846
- It's okay.
- I've just been such a klutz all day.

221
00:20:20,930 --> 00:20:22,431
It's all right.

222
00:20:22,515 --> 00:20:25,559
Sprained this ankle. Oh, my goodness.
I'm so sorry.

223
00:20:25,643 --> 00:20:29,522
- I'm so sorry to fall on you like that.
- That's all right. Don't worry about it.

224
00:20:29,605 --> 00:20:31,982
- I'm Meryl.
- Hi, I'm Truman.

225
00:20:32,066 --> 00:20:33,526
Hey, nice to meet you.

226
00:21:59,153 --> 00:22:03,532
- Truman, you've studied enough.
- No. I got to commit this to memory.

227
00:22:03,741 --> 00:22:05,576
Come on, Truman,
one ice-cold brewski.

228
00:22:05,659 --> 00:22:06,911
Come on.

229
00:22:07,453 --> 00:22:10,748
You're going to have to copy off me,
so be careful.

230
00:22:13,334 --> 00:22:15,377
You're a better person than I am.

231
00:22:15,461 --> 00:22:16,712
- See you later.
- Okay.

232
00:22:16,795 --> 00:22:18,172
- Bye.
- Bye.

233
00:22:19,006 --> 00:22:20,799
See you later, loser.

234
00:23:21,569 --> 00:23:22,611
Hi.

235
00:23:27,533 --> 00:23:30,411
<i>- Konnichi-wa.</i>
- What?

236
00:23:31,036 --> 00:23:32,705
You take Japanese.

237
00:23:33,831 --> 00:23:35,165
Yes.

238
00:23:38,252 --> 00:23:39,753
Lauren, right?

239
00:23:40,296 --> 00:23:41,463
It's on the...

240
00:23:43,173 --> 00:23:44,675
Lauren. Right.

241
00:23:46,093 --> 00:23:47,845
I'm Truman Burbank.

242
00:23:48,345 --> 00:23:50,556
Yeah, I know.

243
00:23:51,515 --> 00:23:54,101
You know, Truman,
I'm not allowed to talk to you.

244
00:23:54,184 --> 00:23:55,394
Really?

245
00:23:58,188 --> 00:24:01,817
Yeah. I can understand that.
I'm a pretty dangerous character.

246
00:24:01,900 --> 00:24:04,111
I'm sorry. It's not up to me.

247
00:24:04,987 --> 00:24:07,072
A girl's got to be careful.

248
00:24:09,908 --> 00:24:13,037
- You have a boyfriend, right?
- No, it's not that.

249
00:24:13,120 --> 00:24:16,665
Was it Meryl, that girl that was with me?
We're not... We don't...

250
00:24:17,583 --> 00:24:19,168
We're just friends.

251
00:24:19,251 --> 00:24:21,920
- It's nothing like that.
- It's how I look?

252
00:24:22,004 --> 00:24:23,505
Not your type?

253
00:24:24,506 --> 00:24:25,549
No.

254
00:24:27,551 --> 00:24:28,552
I like your pin.

255
00:24:29,762 --> 00:24:31,889
I was wondering that myself.

256
00:24:33,390 --> 00:24:35,893
Would you want to maybe, possibly,

257
00:24:36,435 --> 00:24:39,938
sometime go out
for some pizza or something?

258
00:24:40,189 --> 00:24:41,649
Like, Friday?

259
00:24:42,775 --> 00:24:44,109
- Saturday?
- I can't.

260
00:24:44,193 --> 00:24:46,153
Sunday, Monday, Tuesday?

261
00:24:50,574 --> 00:24:53,243
- We have finals tomorrow.
- Yeah, I know.

262
00:24:54,411 --> 00:24:56,914
If we don't go now, it won't happen.

263
00:24:57,915 --> 00:25:01,460
Do you understand?
So what do you want to do?

264
00:25:35,953 --> 00:25:38,622
Please keep your hands inside the car!

265
00:25:55,931 --> 00:25:58,392
This is my favorite pizza place.

266
00:25:58,475 --> 00:25:59,518
Tony!

267
00:25:59,643 --> 00:26:01,645
One large, extra plankton.

268
00:26:02,396 --> 00:26:05,774
We have so little time.
They're going to be here any minute.

269
00:26:05,899 --> 00:26:08,819
- Who are?
- They don't want me talking to you.

270
00:26:09,319 --> 00:26:10,946
Then don't talk.

271
00:26:25,169 --> 00:26:26,670
They're here.

272
00:26:27,963 --> 00:26:29,506
- Truman.
- What do they want?

273
00:26:29,590 --> 00:26:31,717
Listen to me.
Everybody knows about you.

274
00:26:31,800 --> 00:26:33,510
Everybody knows everything you do.

275
00:26:33,594 --> 00:26:35,596
They're pretending, Truman.
Do you understand?

276
00:26:35,679 --> 00:26:37,264
- Everybody's pretending.
- I don't know.

277
00:26:37,347 --> 00:26:39,266
No, my name's not Lauren. It's Sylvia.

278
00:26:39,349 --> 00:26:40,642
- My name's Sylvia.
- Sylvia?

279
00:26:40,726 --> 00:26:43,103
- Yeah.
- Lauren, sweetheart, not again.

280
00:26:43,187 --> 00:26:46,106
- Wait a minute. Who are you?
- I'm her father.

281
00:26:46,356 --> 00:26:49,109
- I've never even seen him before.
- We weren't doing anything.

282
00:26:49,193 --> 00:26:51,945
He's lying.
Truman, please don't listen to him.

283
00:26:52,029 --> 00:26:56,784
Everything I've told you is the truth.
This, it's fake. It's all for you.

284
00:26:56,867 --> 00:26:59,703
- I don't understand.
- The sky and sea, everything, it's a set.

285
00:26:59,787 --> 00:27:00,788
It's a show.

286
00:27:00,871 --> 00:27:03,248
Everybody's watching you.
Please don't listen to him.

287
00:27:03,332 --> 00:27:05,459
He's going to lie to you.
They're watching us now.

288
00:27:05,542 --> 00:27:08,545
- I want to know what's going on.
- Schizophrenia. She has episodes.

289
00:27:08,629 --> 00:27:09,963
We've tried everything.

290
00:27:10,047 --> 00:27:13,383
Hypnotism, shock therapy. Don't worry.

291
00:27:13,467 --> 00:27:15,511
- Truman!
- You're not the first.

292
00:27:15,594 --> 00:27:18,972
You're not the first. She brings
all her boyfriends down here.

293
00:27:19,056 --> 00:27:21,642
What's he saying? Truman, he's lying.

294
00:27:22,559 --> 00:27:24,895
- Get out of here. Come and find me.
- Don't worry.

295
00:27:24,978 --> 00:27:28,440
We're going to Fiji.
Fiji. We're moving to Fiji.

296
00:27:28,524 --> 00:27:29,608
Fiji?

297
00:27:41,578 --> 00:27:42,788
Sylvia!

298
00:27:42,871 --> 00:27:43,872
Hey!

299
00:27:53,465 --> 00:27:55,926
Why didn't he just follow her to Fiji?

300
00:27:56,009 --> 00:28:00,472
His mother got sick, really sick.
He couldn't leave her. He's kind.

301
00:28:00,556 --> 00:28:02,307
Maybe he's too kind.

302
00:28:02,891 --> 00:28:05,519
I can't believe he married Meryl
on the rebound.

303
00:28:05,602 --> 00:28:06,937
Excuse me.

304
00:28:07,062 --> 00:28:08,313
Come on, Sal.

305
00:28:08,397 --> 00:28:11,483
We've already got this
on the greatest hits tape.

306
00:28:11,567 --> 00:28:12,609
Can I borrow that?

307
00:28:59,656 --> 00:29:01,575
Close, but no cigar.

308
00:29:29,937 --> 00:29:32,606
<i>And it's another beautiful day
in paradise, folks,</i>

309
00:29:32,689 --> 00:29:35,442
<i>but don't forget to buckle up
out there in radioland.</i>

310
00:29:35,525 --> 00:29:37,653
<i>Remember, a good driver...</i>

311
00:29:46,495 --> 00:29:48,121
<i>...wait for the cue.</i>

312
00:29:49,915 --> 00:29:51,416
<i>Stand by, one.</i>

313
00:29:52,042 --> 00:29:53,835
<i>Countdown to action.</i>

314
00:29:53,961 --> 00:29:55,462
<i>Stand by, one.</i>

315
00:29:58,465 --> 00:30:01,510
<i>He's heading west on Stewart.
Stand by, all extras.</i>

316
00:30:01,593 --> 00:30:05,931
<i>He'll be on you in about 90 seconds.
Props, make sure the coffee's hot.</i>

317
00:30:06,056 --> 00:30:09,226
<i>Okay, he's making his turn
onto Lancaster Square.</i>

318
00:30:11,812 --> 00:30:13,563
<i>Oh, my God! He nearly hit her.</i>

319
00:30:13,647 --> 00:30:15,816
<i>Something's wrong.
Change frequencies.</i>

320
00:30:21,196 --> 00:30:22,906
<i>Sorry about that, folks.</i>

321
00:30:22,990 --> 00:30:25,325
<i>I guess we picked up
a police frequency or something.</i>

322
00:30:25,409 --> 00:30:28,328
<i>It sometimes happens,
and it can drive you crazy.</i>

323
00:30:28,412 --> 00:30:30,539
<i>Okay, it's Classical Clive back in here</i>

324
00:30:30,622 --> 00:30:33,166
<i>and we've still got
some great music up ahead,</i>

325
00:30:33,250 --> 00:30:34,501
<i>but don't forget to buckle up.</i>

326
00:30:34,584 --> 00:30:37,212
<i>Remember safety.
A good driver is a safe driver.</i>

327
00:30:37,295 --> 00:30:39,423
<i>A safe driver is what? Yes...</i>

328
00:30:55,397 --> 00:30:56,940
Morning, ma'am.

329
00:32:36,706 --> 00:32:39,042
- I love that idea.
- It's pretty cool, isn't it?

330
00:33:43,565 --> 00:33:44,774
Can I help?

331
00:33:44,858 --> 00:33:47,235
Yeah. I have an appointment
at Gable Enterprises.

332
00:33:47,319 --> 00:33:48,778
They went bust.

333
00:33:53,909 --> 00:33:55,994
- What's happening?
- Nothing.

334
00:33:56,077 --> 00:33:59,206
- Just tell me what's happening.
- Got to go, sir. We're remodeling.

335
00:33:59,289 --> 00:34:01,291
No, you're not.
What are those people doing?

336
00:34:01,374 --> 00:34:03,084
It's none of your business!

337
00:34:03,168 --> 00:34:05,629
If you don't tell me what's happening,
I'll report you!

338
00:34:05,712 --> 00:34:07,464
You're trespassing.

339
00:34:38,745 --> 00:34:39,955
Marlon.

340
00:34:40,497 --> 00:34:43,250
- Truman. What are you doing here?
- I got to talk to you.

341
00:34:43,333 --> 00:34:45,210
It's a bad time, okay? I'm way behind.

342
00:34:45,293 --> 00:34:47,837
I'm onto something, Marlon.
Something big.

343
00:34:47,963 --> 00:34:51,007
- You okay? You look like shit.
- I think I'm mixed up in something.

344
00:34:51,091 --> 00:34:52,133
Mixed up in what?

345
00:34:52,217 --> 00:34:53,969
There's no point trying to explain it,

346
00:34:54,052 --> 00:34:57,180
but a lot of strange things
have been happening.

347
00:35:00,558 --> 00:35:04,271
The people on the elevator.
There was no backing on it.

348
00:35:04,354 --> 00:35:06,898
I looked out. There was people there.

349
00:35:06,982 --> 00:35:10,193
And on the radio on the way to work,
it starts following me along,

350
00:35:10,277 --> 00:35:11,987
talking about everything that I'm doing.

351
00:35:12,070 --> 00:35:14,739
- Know what I mean?
- Truman, this is one of your fantasies...

352
00:35:14,823 --> 00:35:16,241
I think this is about my dad.

353
00:35:16,324 --> 00:35:18,535
- Your dad?
- I think he's alive.

354
00:35:19,369 --> 00:35:23,415
Yeah. I'll tell you about it later.
I'm definitely being followed.

355
00:35:23,873 --> 00:35:24,916
Who?

356
00:35:26,710 --> 00:35:30,171
It's hard to tell.
They look just like regular people.

357
00:35:33,508 --> 00:35:37,095
- How about those two?
- I don't know. Could be.

358
00:35:38,096 --> 00:35:41,891
It's when I'm unpredictable, that's...
They can't, you know.

359
00:35:43,226 --> 00:35:45,687
- Did anything happen?
- No.

360
00:35:46,146 --> 00:35:47,981
We gotta get out of here.
You ready to go?

361
00:35:48,064 --> 00:35:49,941
- No. I just came here.
- Come on.

362
00:35:50,025 --> 00:35:51,735
I told you I can't.

363
00:35:55,405 --> 00:35:57,907
You're going to get both our asses fired,
you know that?

364
00:35:57,991 --> 00:36:00,160
- Okay, man, let's do it.
- What?

365
00:36:00,243 --> 00:36:02,370
Whatever you say, I'm game.

366
00:36:02,454 --> 00:36:04,956
- What are you talking about?
- Yes, sirree.

367
00:36:05,081 --> 00:36:07,584
Your birthday comes but once a year.

368
00:36:10,670 --> 00:36:13,256
Maybe I'm being set up for something.

369
00:36:13,757 --> 00:36:15,508
You ever think about that, Marlon?

370
00:36:15,592 --> 00:36:18,678
Like your whole life
has been building toward something?

371
00:36:18,762 --> 00:36:19,763
No.

372
00:36:22,182 --> 00:36:24,809
When you were hauling chickens
in the summer for Kaiser,

373
00:36:24,893 --> 00:36:27,437
what was the furthest
you ever got off the island?

374
00:36:27,520 --> 00:36:30,982
Went all over.
Never found a place like this, though.

375
00:36:32,484 --> 00:36:35,320
Look at that sunset, Truman.
It's perfect.

376
00:36:36,196 --> 00:36:37,280
Yeah.

377
00:36:38,281 --> 00:36:39,991
That's the big guy.

378
00:36:40,867 --> 00:36:43,912
- Quite a paintbrush he's got.
- Yep.

379
00:36:48,041 --> 00:36:50,460
Just between you and me, Marlon,

380
00:36:52,003 --> 00:36:54,130
I'm going away for a while.

381
00:36:55,340 --> 00:36:57,634
- Really?
- Yeah.

382
00:36:59,636 --> 00:37:01,096
Little angel.

383
00:37:07,560 --> 00:37:09,145
My little clown.

384
00:37:11,398 --> 00:37:12,941
Old carrot top.

385
00:37:13,650 --> 00:37:15,318
The best of both of us.

386
00:37:17,112 --> 00:37:19,656
We should be
getting you home, Mother.

387
00:37:19,739 --> 00:37:23,201
Hold on a minute.
Here's us at Mt. Rushmore.

388
00:37:23,284 --> 00:37:25,578
Do you remember, Truman,
when Dad was still with us?

389
00:37:25,662 --> 00:37:29,124
That was quite a drive.
You slept the whole way there.

390
00:37:29,874 --> 00:37:31,501
It looks so small.

391
00:37:31,584 --> 00:37:33,837
Things always do
when you look back, darling.

392
00:37:33,920 --> 00:37:35,380
Look, Truman.

393
00:37:35,713 --> 00:37:38,258
The happiest day of our lives. Look.

394
00:37:40,927 --> 00:37:43,096
Jean, Jodie, Joanne.

395
00:37:43,179 --> 00:37:45,682
Doesn't she look beautiful, Truman?

396
00:37:46,641 --> 00:37:48,226
She still does.

397
00:37:48,309 --> 00:37:51,020
And there's lots of pages left over
for baby photos.

398
00:37:51,104 --> 00:37:54,691
I would like to hold a grandchild
in my arms before I go.

399
00:37:55,525 --> 00:37:57,444
Angela, we really should
be getting you home.

400
00:37:57,527 --> 00:38:00,029
- I'll take her.
- No. You stay, relax.

401
00:38:00,113 --> 00:38:01,823
Enjoy yourself.
Your favorite show will be coming on.

402
00:38:01,906 --> 00:38:02,949
You sure?

403
00:38:03,032 --> 00:38:04,951
Besides, we have something
to discuss.

404
00:38:05,910 --> 00:38:09,539
- A certain person's birthday.
- I see.

405
00:38:11,124 --> 00:38:14,627
<i>And there'll be another episode of</i>
I Love Lucy <i>same time tomorrow.</i>

406
00:38:14,711 --> 00:38:17,547
<i>But right now,
it's time for</i> Golden Oldies.

407
00:38:17,630 --> 00:38:20,300
<i>Tonight, we present
the enduring, much-loved classic,</i>

408
00:38:20,383 --> 00:38:22,469
Show Me the Way to Go Home.

409
00:38:22,552 --> 00:38:24,762
<i>A hymn of praise to small-town life,</i>

410
00:38:24,846 --> 00:38:27,140
<i>where we learn
that you don't have to leave home</i>

411
00:38:27,223 --> 00:38:31,853
<i>to discover what the world's all about,
and that no one is poor who has friends.</i>

412
00:38:32,479 --> 00:38:36,858
<i>Full of laughter and love, pain and
sadness, but ultimately redemption,</i>

413
00:38:36,941 --> 00:38:39,652
<i>we share the trials and tribulations
of the Abbott family.</i>

414
00:38:39,736 --> 00:38:42,655
<i>Note the touching performance
of Ronald Brierly as Uncle Bunny.</i>

415
00:38:42,739 --> 00:38:45,325
<i>That scene with the bowl of cherries
is going to have you</i>

416
00:38:45,408 --> 00:38:48,328
<i>splitting your sides
with laughter all over again.</i>

417
00:38:48,411 --> 00:38:52,373
<i>And there'll be tears, too,
when David and Jennifer are reunited.</i>

418
00:38:52,457 --> 00:38:56,294
<i>But enough from me.
Let's join the Abbotts in Camden village.</i>

419
00:39:23,655 --> 00:39:25,406
Thank you, sweetie.

420
00:39:29,285 --> 00:39:32,622
I need to talk to you,
but let's go outside.

421
00:39:33,414 --> 00:39:37,460
- Sweetie, I'd love to, but I'm really late.
- What's your rush?

422
00:39:38,670 --> 00:39:39,879
Surgery.

423
00:39:39,963 --> 00:39:43,424
There was that elevator disaster
downtown. It was on the news last night.

424
00:39:43,508 --> 00:39:45,218
This cable just snapped.

425
00:39:45,301 --> 00:39:47,845
This elevator,
it just plummeted down 10 flights.

426
00:39:47,929 --> 00:39:50,390
The non-union workers. Just monsters.

427
00:39:50,473 --> 00:39:53,101
That building, it's right next door
to where you work.

428
00:39:53,184 --> 00:39:55,186
Can you imagine
if you had been in there?

429
00:39:55,270 --> 00:39:56,813
It's not even worth thinking about.

430
00:39:56,896 --> 00:39:59,816
Anyway, I have an amputation
on one of the young women

431
00:39:59,899 --> 00:40:03,403
who was in that elevator.
She's very young. It's very sad.

432
00:40:03,486 --> 00:40:06,948
- Anyway, wish me luck.
- I'll cross my fingers for you.

433
00:40:49,240 --> 00:40:52,410
Excuse me. Hi. Excuse me.
May I help you?

434
00:40:54,078 --> 00:40:58,207
Yes. I'm looking for my wife,
Nurse Burbank. It's very important.

435
00:40:58,291 --> 00:41:01,669
I'm afraid that that's not possible.
She's in pre-op.

436
00:41:02,462 --> 00:41:05,048
Sure. Okay, fine.

437
00:41:05,465 --> 00:41:08,134
- Can you pass along a message?
- I'll try.

438
00:41:08,217 --> 00:41:11,971
Can you tell her I had to go to Fiji,
and that I'll call her when I get there?

439
00:41:12,055 --> 00:41:15,725
- When you get to Fiji?
- You got it.

440
00:41:15,808 --> 00:41:19,270
- Fine. I'll tell her.
- Thank you so much.

441
00:41:46,047 --> 00:41:47,924
- Sorry.
- It's okay.

442
00:41:49,175 --> 00:41:51,511
Here, let me help you with that.

443
00:41:55,848 --> 00:41:57,183
He's here.

444
00:41:59,394 --> 00:42:00,603
I know.

445
00:42:01,604 --> 00:42:02,855
Scalpel.

446
00:42:09,529 --> 00:42:13,199
I'm now making my primary incision

447
00:42:13,825 --> 00:42:16,869
just above the right knee.

448
00:42:19,872 --> 00:42:20,873
Hold her.

449
00:42:21,958 --> 00:42:23,334
Nicely done.

450
00:42:23,876 --> 00:42:26,713
This isn't going to be pretty.
Unless you're family...

451
00:42:26,796 --> 00:42:29,298
It's just beautiful. Beautiful job.

452
00:42:31,217 --> 00:42:33,803
I'll just let someone else tidy up here.

453
00:42:58,327 --> 00:43:00,830
- I'm sorry to keep you.
- That's okay.

454
00:43:02,874 --> 00:43:06,669
- How can I help?
- I would like to book a flight to Fiji.

455
00:43:08,838 --> 00:43:11,048
When would you like to leave?

456
00:43:12,008 --> 00:43:13,176
Today.

457
00:43:30,943 --> 00:43:34,572
I'm sorry. I don't have anything
for at least a month.

458
00:43:35,031 --> 00:43:37,533
- A month?
- It's the busy season.

459
00:43:39,827 --> 00:43:41,954
You want to book the flight?

460
00:43:42,789 --> 00:43:46,501
It doesn't matter.
I'll make other arrangements, okay?

461
00:43:49,712 --> 00:43:52,632
Last call for Chicago!

462
00:43:52,965 --> 00:43:55,384
All aboard!

463
00:44:00,515 --> 00:44:01,849
Thank you.

464
00:44:04,727 --> 00:44:06,729
Windy city, here we come.

465
00:44:08,856 --> 00:44:10,066
- Hi.
- Hi.

466
00:44:13,611 --> 00:44:15,404
Hello. Hi.

467
00:44:17,406 --> 00:44:18,449
Sisters.

468
00:44:18,533 --> 00:44:22,245
- Mom, isn't that...
- Face the front.

469
00:44:49,689 --> 00:44:52,191
Everybody off. We've got a problem.

470
00:45:11,752 --> 00:45:13,296
I'm sorry, son.

471
00:45:27,143 --> 00:45:29,854
His father was from Chicago,
wasn't he?

472
00:45:30,104 --> 00:45:33,816
No. His dentist was from Pensacola.
His father was from Des Moines.

473
00:45:33,900 --> 00:45:35,985
But how come he wants to go
to Chicago?

474
00:45:36,068 --> 00:45:38,696
He's not going to Chicago.
He's not going anywhere.

475
00:45:38,779 --> 00:45:40,865
He has to have it out with Meryl.

476
00:45:56,839 --> 00:45:58,007
Truman?

477
00:46:03,304 --> 00:46:06,515
- Honey, are you okay?
- Get in.

478
00:46:10,186 --> 00:46:11,395
Truman.

479
00:46:12,688 --> 00:46:13,814
Look.

480
00:46:17,401 --> 00:46:18,569
What?

481
00:46:19,737 --> 00:46:22,365
I predict that in just a moment,

482
00:46:24,033 --> 00:46:28,204
we will see a lady on a red bike,
followed by a man with flowers

483
00:46:29,163 --> 00:46:32,208
and a Volkswagen Beetle
with a dented fender.

484
00:46:32,541 --> 00:46:34,627
- Truman, please.
- Look.

485
00:46:40,424 --> 00:46:41,634
Lady,

486
00:46:43,135 --> 00:46:44,470
flowers,

487
00:46:46,180 --> 00:46:47,765
and...

488
00:46:50,226 --> 00:46:53,145
- Truman, this is silly.
- There it is!

489
00:46:53,229 --> 00:46:55,564
There's that dented Beetle! Yes!

