01:03:32,060 --> 01:03:35,230
<i>The first intruder
to be a former cast member.</i>

733
01:03:35,855 --> 01:03:36,982
A dead one at that.

734
01:03:37,065 --> 01:03:40,652
<i>Got to say, writing Kirk back in,
masterstroke.</i>

735
01:03:41,111 --> 01:03:43,613
<i>Since Kirk started this whole crisis
in Truman's life,</i>

736
01:03:43,697 --> 01:03:46,992
<i>I came to the conclusion that he was
the only one who could end it.</i>

737
01:03:47,075 --> 01:03:48,201
Truman!

738
01:03:48,284 --> 01:03:49,577
Truman, no!

739
01:03:50,578 --> 01:03:51,746
That's off-limits.

740
01:03:51,830 --> 01:03:55,542
- Why? What's over there?
- Nothing. It's dangerous. That's all.

741
01:03:55,792 --> 01:03:58,003
You've got to know
your limitations, Truman.

742
01:03:58,086 --> 01:04:02,215
<i>But let's remind viewers of exactly why
Dad was written out in the first place.</i>

743
01:04:02,340 --> 01:04:05,677
<i>As Truman grew up,
we were forced to manufacture ways</i>

744
01:04:05,760 --> 01:04:07,512
<i>to keep him on the island.</i>

745
01:04:07,804 --> 01:04:10,515
I'd like to be an explorer,
like the great Magellan.

746
01:04:10,598 --> 01:04:12,100
You're too late.

747
01:04:12,183 --> 01:04:14,561
There's really nothing left to explore.

748
01:04:19,065 --> 01:04:21,693
<i>Finally, I came up with the concept
of Kirk's drowning.</i>

749
01:04:21,776 --> 01:04:24,904
<i>Most effective. Truman's been
terrified of the water ever since.</i>

750
01:04:24,988 --> 01:04:27,824
<i>When Kirk read the synopsis
for the </i>Death At Sea <i>episode,</i>

751
01:04:27,907 --> 01:04:31,369
<i>he was disappointed, to say the least.</i>

752
01:04:32,620 --> 01:04:35,040
<i>I'm sure that's what caused him
to break back onto the set.</i>

753
01:04:35,123 --> 01:04:38,460
<i>But how do you intend to explain
his 22-year absence?</i>

754
01:04:40,378 --> 01:04:42,672
- Amnesia.
<i>- Brilliant.</i>

755
01:04:43,465 --> 01:04:45,300
<i>Let's take some viewer phone calls.</i>

756
01:04:45,383 --> 01:04:48,303
<i>Charlotte, North Carolina,
you're on with Christof.</i>

757
01:04:49,387 --> 01:04:50,847
<i>Yeah, hi, Christof.</i>

758
01:04:51,139 --> 01:04:54,642
<i>I was just wondering how many
cameras you got there in that town.</i>

759
01:04:55,101 --> 01:04:57,228
<i>Somewhere in the vicinity of 5,000.</i>

760
01:04:57,645 --> 01:05:02,358
<i>- That's a lot of cameras.
- Remember, we started with just one.</i>

761
01:05:04,110 --> 01:05:06,154
<i>He was curious from birth.</i>

762
01:05:07,155 --> 01:05:10,784
<i>Premature by two weeks. It was almost
as if he couldn't wait to get started.</i>

763
01:05:10,867 --> 01:05:13,161
<i>And his eagerness to leave
his mother's womb</i>

764
01:05:13,244 --> 01:05:15,747
<i>was the very reason he was the one
who was selected.</i>

765
01:05:15,830 --> 01:05:18,541
<i>In competition
with five other unwanted pregnancies,</i>

766
01:05:18,625 --> 01:05:21,419
<i>the casting of a show,
determined by an air date,</i>

767
01:05:21,544 --> 01:05:23,838
<i>Truman was the one who
arrived on cue.</i>

768
01:05:28,635 --> 01:05:31,513
<i>Incidentally, I believe
Truman is the first child</i>

769
01:05:31,596 --> 01:05:34,099
<i>to have been legally adopted
by a corporation.</i>

770
01:05:34,182 --> 01:05:35,308
<i>That's correct.</i>

771
01:05:35,391 --> 01:05:37,769
<i>The show has generated
enormous revenues,</i>

772
01:05:37,852 --> 01:05:41,106
<i>now equivalent to the gross national
product of a small country.</i>

773
01:05:41,189 --> 01:05:42,357
<i>People forget it takes</i>

774
01:05:42,440 --> 01:05:45,151
<i>the population of an entire country
to keep the show running.</i>

775
01:05:45,235 --> 01:05:48,905
<i>Since the show is on 24 hours a day
without commercial interruption,</i>

776
01:05:48,988 --> 01:05:52,534
<i>all those staggering revenues
are generated by product placement.</i>

777
01:05:52,951 --> 01:05:55,286
<i>That's true.
Everything on the show is for sale.</i>

778
01:05:55,370 --> 01:05:58,665
<i>From the actors' wardrobe, food
products, to the very homes they live in.</i>

779
01:05:58,748 --> 01:06:01,084
<i>All of it available in the </i>Truman <i>catalog</i>

780
01:06:01,167 --> 01:06:02,544
<i>and operators are standing by.</i>

781
01:06:02,627 --> 01:06:04,379
<i>Christof, let me ask you.</i>

782
01:06:04,796 --> 01:06:08,049
<i>Why do you think
that Truman has never come close</i>

783
01:06:08,550 --> 01:06:11,678
<i>to discovering the true nature
of his world until now?</i>

784
01:06:12,137 --> 01:06:15,181
<i>We accept the reality of the world
with which we are presented.</i>

785
01:06:15,265 --> 01:06:16,891
<i>It's as simple as that.</i>

786
01:06:17,517 --> 01:06:19,144
<i>The Hague for Christof.</i>

787
01:06:19,227 --> 01:06:21,437
<i>Hello? The Hague?</i>

788
01:06:22,939 --> 01:06:26,526
<i>All right, we've lost that call. Let's go
to Hollywood. You're on </i>Trutalk.

789
01:06:26,609 --> 01:06:29,237
Hi, I'd just like to say one thing.

790
01:06:29,320 --> 01:06:30,989
You're a liar and a manipulator.

791
01:06:31,072 --> 01:06:33,366
<i>And what you've done to Truman
is sick.</i>

792
01:06:34,909 --> 01:06:37,036
<i>We remember this voice, don't we?</i>

793
01:06:38,288 --> 01:06:40,790
<i>- How could we forget?
- Let's go to another call.</i>

794
01:06:40,874 --> 01:06:44,169
<i>No. It's fine, Mike.</i>

795
01:06:44,586 --> 01:06:47,505
<i>I love to reminisce
with former members of the cast.</i>

796
01:06:48,756 --> 01:06:50,008
<i>Sylvia,</i>

797
01:06:50,967 --> 01:06:53,803
<i>as you announced
so melodramatically to the world,</i>

798
01:06:55,096 --> 01:06:58,349
<i>you think because you batted your eyes
at Truman once,</i>

799
01:06:59,726 --> 01:07:01,186
<i>flirted with him,</i>

800
01:07:01,519 --> 01:07:03,813
<i>stole a few minutes of airtime with him</i>

801
01:07:03,897 --> 01:07:07,066
<i>to thrust yourself and your politics
into the limelight,</i>

802
01:07:07,150 --> 01:07:10,862
<i>that you know him?
That you know what's right for him?</i>

803
01:07:11,362 --> 01:07:13,990
<i>You really think you're in a position
to judge him?</i>

804
01:07:14,073 --> 01:07:16,201
What right do you have to take a baby

805
01:07:16,284 --> 01:07:18,953
and turn his life
into some kind of mockery?

806
01:07:19,787 --> 01:07:21,581
Don't you ever feel guilty?

807
01:07:23,249 --> 01:07:27,003
<i>I have given Truman a chance
to lead a normal life.</i>

808
01:07:28,338 --> 01:07:31,382
<i>The world, the place you live in,</i>

809
01:07:32,467 --> 01:07:33,885
<i>is the sick place.</i>

810
01:07:36,012 --> 01:07:38,056
<i>Seahaven is the way
the world should be.</i>

811
01:07:38,139 --> 01:07:41,851
He's not a performer. He's a prisoner.
Look at what you've done to him!

812
01:07:41,935 --> 01:07:43,645
<i>He could leave at any time.</i>

813
01:07:43,853 --> 01:07:46,397
<i>If his was more than
just a vague ambition,</i>

814
01:07:46,481 --> 01:07:50,068
<i>if he was absolutely determined
to discover the truth,</i>

815
01:07:51,277 --> 01:07:53,488
<i>there's no way we could prevent him.</i>

816
01:07:53,780 --> 01:07:56,449
<i>I think what distresses you,</i>

817
01:07:57,408 --> 01:08:00,662
<i>really, caller, is that ultimately</i>

818
01:08:01,913 --> 01:08:05,541
<i>Truman prefers his cell, as you call it.</i>

819
01:08:05,959 --> 01:08:07,669
That's where you're wrong.

820
01:08:08,169 --> 01:08:10,922
You're so wrong,
and he'll prove you wrong.

821
01:08:11,339 --> 01:08:15,551
<i>Aside from the heated comments
of a very vocal minority,</i>

822
01:08:15,760 --> 01:08:18,471
<i>it's been
an overwhelmingly positive experience.</i>

823
01:08:18,680 --> 01:08:21,015
<i>Yes. For Truman
and for the viewing public.</i>

824
01:08:21,099 --> 01:08:23,017
<i>Christof, I can't thank you enough</i>

825
01:08:23,101 --> 01:08:25,561
<i>for giving so generously
of your time tonight.</i>

826
01:08:25,645 --> 01:08:28,523
<i>I think it's safe to say that
now that this crisis is behind us</i>

827
01:08:28,606 --> 01:08:30,275
<i>and that Truman's back to his old self,</i>

828
01:08:30,358 --> 01:08:33,695
<i>we can look forward
to some exciting new developments.</i>

829
01:08:33,778 --> 01:08:37,115
<i>Mike, the big news is
that Meryl will be leaving Truman</i>

830
01:08:37,198 --> 01:08:38,783
<i>in an upcoming episode.</i>

831
01:08:38,866 --> 01:08:41,536
<i>And a new romantic interest
will be introduced.</i>

832
01:08:42,203 --> 01:08:46,541
<i>I'm determined that television's first
on-air conception will still take place.</i>

833
01:08:46,958 --> 01:08:50,962
<i>Another television milestone
straight ahead. You heard it here first.</i>

834
01:08:51,045 --> 01:08:53,798
<i>It has been a singular honor
and a pleasure, sir.</i>

835
01:08:53,881 --> 01:08:56,467
<i>- Christof, thank you.
- Thank you, Mike.</i>

836
01:10:14,921 --> 01:10:16,547
- Simeon.
- What?

837
01:10:20,968 --> 01:10:22,512
Is he looking at us?

838
01:10:22,929 --> 01:10:24,889
Jesus, do you think he knows?

839
01:10:26,307 --> 01:10:27,308
<i>Hello?</i>

840
01:10:27,809 --> 01:10:29,352
Better call Christof.

841
01:10:29,477 --> 01:10:31,479
<i>Hello? Come in, Major Burbank.</i>

842
01:10:43,658 --> 01:10:44,659
Jesus.

843
01:10:48,996 --> 01:10:51,916
- He's back to his old self.
- Thank God.

844
01:10:59,757 --> 01:11:02,218
That's an unusual cat, my man.

845
01:11:07,098 --> 01:11:10,351
<i>I hereby proclaim this planet...</i>

846
01:11:15,106 --> 01:11:17,900
<i>Trumania of the Burbank galaxy.</i>

847
01:11:20,361 --> 01:11:22,697
- Is he gonna go?
- Okay, hallway camera ready.

848
01:11:24,574 --> 01:11:25,950
<i>That one's for free.</i>

849
01:11:26,033 --> 01:11:27,994
Keep up with him,
'cause he'll move fast.

850
01:11:28,077 --> 01:11:30,204
Stand by, all house cameras.

851
01:11:31,247 --> 01:11:33,458
- Morning!
- Good morning.

852
01:11:33,624 --> 01:11:35,293
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

853
01:11:35,376 --> 01:11:37,044
In case I don't see you...

854
01:11:37,128 --> 01:11:39,672
Good afternoon, good evening,
and good night.

855
01:11:42,091 --> 01:11:44,469
- Good afternoon...
- Good morning.

856
01:11:44,552 --> 01:11:46,679
...evening and good night.

857
01:11:47,346 --> 01:11:49,474
- Morning, Truman.
- Morning, Spencer.

858
01:11:49,557 --> 01:11:51,851
- How's it going?
- Let me check.

859
01:11:52,643 --> 01:11:54,187
Vital signs are good.

860
01:11:56,564 --> 01:11:57,815
Pluto!

861
01:11:58,357 --> 01:11:59,984
Good morning, Truman.

862
01:12:00,067 --> 01:12:02,820
- Look who's here.
- Beautiful day, isn't it?

863
01:12:03,112 --> 01:12:04,238
Every single day.

864
01:12:04,322 --> 01:12:07,241
The policy, we've thought about it
and we're gonna take it.

865
01:12:07,325 --> 01:12:08,618
- You're kidding?
- No!

866
01:12:08,701 --> 01:12:11,454
Why don't we go up to my office
right now and we'll sign the papers?

867
01:12:11,537 --> 01:12:14,165
Next week would be much better.

868
01:12:14,248 --> 01:12:17,460
- All right. See you guys.
- Okay, bye now. See you next week.

869
01:12:17,543 --> 01:12:20,213
- Give me something to look forward to.
- You got it.

870
01:12:20,296 --> 01:12:22,006
See, this isn't about insurance.

871
01:12:22,423 --> 01:12:26,594
This is about the great variable:
when will death occur?

872
01:12:26,928 --> 01:12:29,013
Could be a week, a month, a year.

873
01:12:30,056 --> 01:12:31,307
Could be today.

874
01:12:33,559 --> 01:12:35,853
"Sunbather, minding his own business,

875
01:12:36,687 --> 01:12:39,774
"stabbed in the heart by the tip
of a runaway beach umbrella."

876
01:12:39,857 --> 01:12:42,401
No way to guard against
that kind of thing.

877
01:12:44,570 --> 01:12:46,030
Sorry, excuse me.

878
01:12:46,239 --> 01:12:48,533
Truman, this is Vivien.
Vivien, this is Truman.

879
01:12:48,616 --> 01:12:50,952
The two of you are gonna be neighbors.

880
01:12:55,039 --> 01:12:58,751
I guess what I'm saying is that life is

881
01:12:59,544 --> 01:13:00,795
fragile.

882
01:13:02,547 --> 01:13:04,173
- Vivien, your office.
- Sorry.

883
01:13:04,257 --> 01:13:07,301
What's that? I'm sorry.

884
01:13:08,344 --> 01:13:09,470
You do?

885
01:13:10,346 --> 01:13:13,307
Great. Let me take your information.

886
01:13:29,615 --> 01:13:31,242
Ready, 2. Go to 2.

887
01:13:35,705 --> 01:13:37,164
And back to medium.

888
01:13:39,208 --> 01:13:40,585
And wide.

889
01:13:48,593 --> 01:13:51,345
I was just trying to train the kid to...

890
01:13:52,263 --> 01:13:53,598
Never mind.

891
01:13:56,809 --> 01:13:58,853
What's he doing in the basement?

892
01:13:59,145 --> 01:14:01,647
He moved down there
after Meryl packed up and left.

893
01:14:01,731 --> 01:14:03,149
Why wasn't I told?

894
01:14:03,232 --> 01:14:05,860
Any unpredictable behavior
has to be reported.

895
01:14:07,278 --> 01:14:09,155
He's just sleeping, I thought.

896
01:14:09,238 --> 01:14:11,782
- This the best shot we've got?
- What's to see?

897
01:14:11,866 --> 01:14:15,494
- What's on the clock cam?
- It's an obstruction.

898
01:14:15,995 --> 01:14:19,749
- What happened down there?
- He was just tidying up his garbage.

899
01:14:20,750 --> 01:14:24,712
I was gonna call you, but halfway
through, he gave up, and he fell asleep.

900
01:14:25,087 --> 01:14:28,257
I wanna check on the setups
for the insurance convention tomorrow.

901
01:14:28,341 --> 01:14:29,717
- Yes.
- Yeah.

902
01:14:30,718 --> 01:14:32,053
Nice move.

903
01:14:41,145 --> 01:14:42,396
There you go.

904
01:14:53,366 --> 01:14:54,742
Isolate the audio.

905
01:14:56,077 --> 01:14:58,079
Give me a close-up on his torso.

906
01:15:00,915 --> 01:15:02,416
He's still breathing.

907
01:15:04,627 --> 01:15:06,295
Where's Chloe? Call him.

908
01:15:06,504 --> 01:15:09,757
- What do you want me to say?
- Tell him it's a wrong number.

909
01:15:13,219 --> 01:15:14,804
What took you so long?

910
01:15:15,262 --> 01:15:17,807
Just had to wait for it. They were busy.

911
01:15:18,724 --> 01:15:21,143
Here. What's going on?

912
01:15:21,977 --> 01:15:23,729
I don't know. They're...

913
01:15:23,896 --> 01:15:26,857
He came down into the room. He did
nothing but stand around for a while.

914
01:15:26,941 --> 01:15:28,442
Shut up and watch it.

915
01:15:29,068 --> 01:15:31,153
Then we went to night vision.

916
01:15:31,946 --> 01:15:33,364
He's asleep.

917
01:15:34,990 --> 01:15:36,242
- There!
- What?

918
01:15:36,659 --> 01:15:38,411
- Zoom in.
- On which?

919
01:15:38,744 --> 01:15:40,329
Under the chair there.

920
01:15:42,790 --> 01:15:44,125
Enhance it.

921
01:15:46,669 --> 01:15:49,171
- Is it...
- My God.

922
01:15:50,965 --> 01:15:54,093
He couldn't have gone up the stairs.
He must still be in the room.

923
01:15:54,176 --> 01:15:55,803
- Get Marlon over there.
- Right away.

924
01:16:11,485 --> 01:16:12,653
Truman!

925
01:16:13,529 --> 01:16:14,822
Surprise party!

926
01:16:16,866 --> 01:16:18,159
Come on, buddy.

927
01:16:18,409 --> 01:16:21,537
I got a six-pack of cold brewskis
with our name on them.

928
01:16:21,662 --> 01:16:23,956
Come on, pal. Come on, buddy.

929
01:16:27,960 --> 01:16:29,044
Shit.

930
01:16:32,339 --> 01:16:34,842
Marlon, find him. He's still in the room.

931
01:16:39,221 --> 01:16:41,140
<i>Come out, come out, wherever you are.</i>

932
01:16:41,223 --> 01:16:43,017
That's good. Keep it light.

933
01:16:43,934 --> 01:16:46,395
<i>I know you're in here.
I'm gonna find you.</i>

934
01:16:49,982 --> 01:16:51,567
Check under the table.

935
01:16:52,985 --> 01:16:54,612
The closet, behind you.

936
01:16:58,616 --> 01:16:59,617
Huh.

937
01:17:01,410 --> 01:17:02,411
Gee.

938
01:17:03,287 --> 01:17:05,498
I wonder where he could possibly be.

939
01:17:13,422 --> 01:17:15,674
The lawn cam, get me the lawn cam.

940
01:17:23,349 --> 01:17:26,018
Don't look in the camera.
Say something. Keep it going.

941
01:17:26,101 --> 01:17:27,228
<i>He's gone.</i>

942
01:17:27,728 --> 01:17:29,563
- Cut transmission!
- Cut transmission?

943
01:17:29,647 --> 01:17:30,898
Cut it!

944
01:17:33,275 --> 01:17:35,152
Jesus! God in heaven!

945
01:17:36,737 --> 01:17:39,073
- Everything's black.
- Give me the phone.

946
01:17:51,919 --> 01:17:54,129
I don't know where he is, but he's gone.

947
01:18:00,511 --> 01:18:03,597
All right. We've got
every available extra looking for him.

948
01:18:03,681 --> 01:18:07,977
The principals are helping out. The
crew, too. So every sector's covered.

949
01:18:08,644 --> 01:18:11,355
- What about prop cars?
- Yes, they've been accounted for.

950
01:18:11,438 --> 01:18:12,857
He has to be on foot.

951
01:18:12,940 --> 01:18:15,860
He has the world's most
recognizable face. He can't disappear.

952
01:18:51,729 --> 01:18:52,813
Go.

953
01:18:53,689 --> 01:18:57,318
Hunt him. Yeah. Go find him, Pluto.

954
01:18:57,902 --> 01:18:59,111
Good dog!

955
01:18:59,194 --> 01:19:00,446
All this fuss.

956
01:19:01,280 --> 01:19:03,282
If he could just hear my voice.

957
01:19:04,241 --> 01:19:05,451
Truman!

958
01:19:08,579 --> 01:19:10,873
Let me try. Truman!

959
01:19:12,166 --> 01:19:14,001
It's me, Dad!

960
01:19:16,295 --> 01:19:17,504
Let's talk.

961
01:19:19,173 --> 01:19:20,674
Yeah, I know.

962
01:19:22,384 --> 01:19:24,303
Just about done with the square.

963
01:19:24,386 --> 01:19:26,972
<i>Got to go back to Barrymore,
check the interiors.</i>

964
01:19:27,056 --> 01:19:29,266
<i>- He's got to be in there.</i>
- Barrymore.

965
01:19:29,683 --> 01:19:31,810
But what about the college?
Who's watching that?

966
01:19:31,894 --> 01:19:32,895
<i>I don't know.</i>

967
01:19:32,978 --> 01:19:35,314
- Send somebody over there, okay?
<i>- All right.</i>

968
01:19:39,568 --> 01:19:41,946
Take another man
and get down there now, all right?

969
01:19:42,029 --> 01:19:44,281
I don't give a damn.
Just find the son of a bitch.

970
01:19:44,365 --> 01:19:45,324
Get some batteries.

971
01:19:45,407 --> 01:19:48,118
This guy's not gonna glow in the dark.
Get them down here.

972
01:19:48,202 --> 01:19:50,913
I don't know what's going on.
Reroute it back to me.

973
01:19:50,996 --> 01:19:54,208
We need more light.
We'll never find him this way.

974
01:19:59,505 --> 01:20:00,881
What time is it?

975
01:20:01,215 --> 01:20:03,509
It's way too early for that.

976
01:20:10,224 --> 01:20:11,392
Cue the sun.

977
01:20:17,982 --> 01:20:19,358
What time is it?

978
01:20:20,359 --> 01:20:22,069
Christof, what's going on?

979
01:20:22,611 --> 01:20:25,572
Did you know there's a rumor
circulating that he's dead?

980
01:20:25,656 --> 01:20:26,824
You hear me?

981
01:20:26,907 --> 01:20:29,201
The media is having a feeding frenzy
over this.

982
01:20:29,284 --> 01:20:31,036
All the phone lines are jammed,

983
01:20:31,120 --> 01:20:32,705
and every network has a pirated shot

984
01:20:32,788 --> 01:20:35,040
of Marlon making an ass of himself
in front of the camera.

985
01:20:35,124 --> 01:20:37,334
The sponsors are threatening
to rip up their contracts.

986
01:20:37,418 --> 01:20:38,836
Why? We're getting higher ratings
with this graphic

987
01:20:38,919 --> 01:20:42,006
than we've ever had on this show.

988
01:20:44,925 --> 01:20:46,218
<i>No sign of him.</i>

989
01:20:46,385 --> 01:20:49,179
Marlon, why don't you head back to town
and join the others?

990
01:20:49,263 --> 01:20:52,224
Everyone else is at first positions, okay?
Thank you.

991
01:20:53,767 --> 01:20:55,978
Everyone's at first positions, right?

992
01:21:11,368 --> 01:21:14,872
We've got the light.
So he's got to be there somewhere.

993
01:21:17,666 --> 01:21:19,376
We're not watching the sea.

994
01:21:19,460 --> 01:21:22,004
Hang on a minute.
Why would we watch the sea?

995
01:21:22,629 --> 01:21:23,964
Sweep the harbor.

996
01:21:24,131 --> 01:21:25,674
Bring up the harbor cameras.

997
01:21:25,758 --> 01:21:28,093
Shift all harbor cameras to computer,
please.

998
01:21:28,177 --> 01:21:29,803
Some of those are out, aren't they?

999
01:21:29,887 --> 01:21:33,307
Yeah. We have four of them down,
but we have the lighthouse cameras up.

1000
01:21:33,390 --> 01:21:35,851
- All buoy cams, please.
- What's happening?

1001
01:21:36,977 --> 01:21:38,604
Long-lens, shore-based cameras.

1002
01:21:38,687 --> 01:21:40,731
- Why are we looking at the water?
- Good.

1003
01:21:40,814 --> 01:21:42,649
Pan and zoom please.

1004
01:21:46,111 --> 01:21:47,321
Truman,

1005
01:21:49,490 --> 01:21:50,991
where are you going?

1006
01:21:52,951 --> 01:21:54,828
How can he sail? He's in insurance.

1007
01:21:54,912 --> 01:21:57,414
- Isn't he terrified of the water?
- Resume transmission.

1008
01:21:57,498 --> 01:21:59,083
Resuming transmission.

1009
01:22:04,296 --> 01:22:07,424
- I got 2-to-1 he doesn't make it.
- I want a piece of that.

1010
01:22:07,508 --> 01:22:09,593
2-to-1 he doesn't make it.

1011
01:22:11,970 --> 01:22:13,680
Just leave them in the car.

1012
01:22:26,735 --> 01:22:30,614
Let's get off this mast shot. We can't
see his face. Go to the cabin cam.

1013
01:22:33,617 --> 01:22:35,160
There. Perfect.

1014
01:22:36,120 --> 01:22:37,663
That's our hero shot.

1015
01:23:03,272 --> 01:23:05,065
Let's get another boat out there.

1016
01:23:05,149 --> 01:23:08,402
Okay. Listen, Gus, I need you to talk
to the guys on the ferry.

1017
01:23:08,485 --> 01:23:11,029
Come on. Get it moving.
Get it out of here.

1018
01:23:13,282 --> 01:23:14,533
Come on.

1019
01:23:15,117 --> 01:23:18,745
- I'm usually the bus driver.
- Bottom line is they can't drive the boat.

1020
01:23:18,954 --> 01:23:20,247
They're actors.

1021
01:23:24,710 --> 01:23:26,170
How do we stop him?

1022
01:23:36,597 --> 01:23:37,806
Okay.

1023
01:23:40,309 --> 01:23:43,937
We're going to be accessing
the weather program now.

1024
01:23:44,605 --> 01:23:48,275
So hold onto your hats. You got that?

1025
01:23:48,775 --> 01:23:52,946
No. I think we're gonna want to localize
the storm over the boat.

1026
01:23:56,033 --> 01:23:58,035
You can get the coordinates for that.

1027
01:23:58,118 --> 01:24:00,746
There's no rescue boat.
He won't know what to do.

1028
01:24:00,829 --> 01:24:03,123
He'll turn back. He'll be too afraid.

1029
01:24:06,543 --> 01:24:07,920
Thar she blows.

1030
01:24:19,765 --> 01:24:20,933
Come on.

1031
01:24:44,665 --> 01:24:46,166
Give me some lightning.

1032
01:24:47,334 --> 01:24:48,418
Again.

1033
01:24:49,002 --> 01:24:50,212
Hit him again!

1034
01:25:01,932 --> 01:25:04,184
For God's sake,
the whole world is watching.

1035
01:25:04,268 --> 01:25:06,436
We can't let him die
in front of a live audience.

1036
01:25:06,520 --> 01:25:08,355
He was born in front of a live audience.

1037
01:25:36,967 --> 01:25:38,802
Come on, Truman!

1038
01:25:42,389 --> 01:25:44,725
You can do it! Hold on!

1039
01:26:10,000 --> 01:26:12,085
Is that the best you can do?

1040
01:26:13,628 --> 01:26:16,757
You're gonna have to kill me!

1041
01:26:17,924 --> 01:26:20,177
<i>What shall we do with a drunken sailor?</i>

1042
01:26:20,260 --> 01:26:22,846
- I demand that you cease transmission.
- Keep running.

1043
01:26:22,971 --> 01:26:27,267
<i>What shall we do with a drunken sailor
Early in the mornin'?</i>

1044
01:26:27,476 --> 01:26:30,020
Increase the wind.

1045
01:26:32,439 --> 01:26:34,900
- I'm telling you for the last time.
- How close is he?

1046
01:26:34,983 --> 01:26:36,401
- Very close.
- Capsize him. Tip him over.

1047
01:26:36,485 --> 01:26:39,363
- Damn you, Christof!
- You can't. He's tied himself to the boat!

1048
01:26:39,446 --> 01:26:40,447
Shut up!

1049
01:26:40,530 --> 01:26:42,324
He's gonna drown,
and he doesn't even care.

1050
01:26:42,407 --> 01:26:43,533
- Do it.
- No.

1051
01:26:43,617 --> 01:26:44,618
Do it!

1052
01:27:39,297 --> 01:27:40,549
That's enough.

1053
01:31:51,591 --> 01:31:53,134
I want to talk to him.

1054
01:32:12,112 --> 01:32:13,321
Truman.

1055
01:32:15,115 --> 01:32:16,408
You can speak.

1056
01:32:18,493 --> 01:32:19,786
<i>I can hear you.</i>

1057
01:32:24,332 --> 01:32:25,458
Who are you?

1058
01:32:25,583 --> 01:32:28,128
I am the creator of a television show

1059
01:32:28,211 --> 01:32:31,214
that gives hope and joy and inspiration
to millions.

1060
01:32:36,136 --> 01:32:37,387
<i>Then who am I?</i>

1061
01:32:37,804 --> 01:32:39,180
You're the star.

1062
01:32:45,270 --> 01:32:46,646
<i>Was nothing real?</i>

1063
01:32:47,272 --> 01:32:48,523
You were real.

1064
01:32:49,983 --> 01:32:52,277
That's what made you so good to watch.

1065
01:32:52,986 --> 01:32:54,529
Listen to me, Truman.

1066
01:32:54,654 --> 01:32:56,823
There's no more truth out there

1067
01:32:57,907 --> 01:33:00,535
than there is in the world
I created for you.

1068
01:33:02,495 --> 01:33:04,038
<i>The same lies,</i>

1069
01:33:05,749 --> 01:33:07,083
<i>the same deceit.</i>

1070
01:33:08,042 --> 01:33:09,461
But in my world

1071
01:33:11,296 --> 01:33:13,006
you have nothing to fear.

1072
01:33:16,384 --> 01:33:18,928
<i>I know you better than
you know yourself.</i>

1073
01:33:19,012 --> 01:33:21,139
You never had a camera in my head.

1074
01:33:22,932 --> 01:33:24,184
You're afraid.

1075
01:33:25,477 --> 01:33:27,270
That's why you can't leave.

1076
01:33:31,941 --> 01:33:33,359
It's okay, Truman.

1077
01:33:34,486 --> 01:33:35,737
I understand.

1078
01:33:37,530 --> 01:33:40,033
I have been watching you
your whole life.

1079
01:33:42,827 --> 01:33:44,954
I was watching when you were born.

1080
01:33:47,373 --> 01:33:49,918
I was watching
when you took your first step.

1081
01:33:54,214 --> 01:33:56,716
<i>I watched you on your first day
of school.</i>

1082
01:33:59,594 --> 01:34:02,138
The episode when you lost
your first tooth.

1083
01:34:06,601 --> 01:34:08,311
You can't leave, Truman.

1084
01:34:09,938 --> 01:34:11,356
Please, God.

1085
01:34:11,439 --> 01:34:12,899
<i>You belong here...</i>

1086
01:34:13,107 --> 01:34:14,317
You can do it.

1087
01:34:16,236 --> 01:34:17,445
...with me.

1088
01:34:19,948 --> 01:34:21,241
Talk to me.

1089
01:34:22,617 --> 01:34:23,868
Say something.

1090
01:34:28,289 --> 01:34:31,417
Say something, God damn it.
You're on television.

1091
01:34:31,793 --> 01:34:33,795
<i>You're live to the whole world.</i>

1092
01:34:51,437 --> 01:34:53,273
In case I don't see you,

1093
01:34:54,440 --> 01:34:56,985
good afternoon, good evening,
and good night.

1094
01:35:00,196 --> 01:35:01,239
Yeah.

1095
01:35:24,345 --> 01:35:25,763
Yeah!

1096
01:35:35,481 --> 01:35:38,526
- He made it! Yeah!
- All right, Truman!

1097
01:35:48,369 --> 01:35:50,872
- Cease transmission.
- Ceasing transmission.

1098
01:35:55,585 --> 01:35:57,879
- You want another slice?
- No. I'm okay.

1099
01:35:58,713 --> 01:36:00,715
What else is on?
Where's the <i>TV Guide?</i>

